1. Introduction to the project


1.1 Outline


  • Period: April 2021 - March 2023


  • Obligation:

    • Members: meetings (up to once a month), field surveys (about once a year), co-authoring a book (final draft by March 2023)

    • Observers: none (valuable comments)


  • Output: An electronic book (free for reading online, hard copy can be ordered with cost)


1.2 Motivation


Proliferation of big data with low or almost no cost. But it is difficult to

  • identify (locate) potential data for specific research


  • process the data into required unit of analysis

Some examples:

light every night (World Bank)

World-Scale OpenStreetMap POIS in CSV (SLIPO)

3. Tools


3.1 Github


  • Git

Global Information Tracker. A version tracker that help programmers to work together in a project.



  • Github

A provider of Internet hosting for software development and version control using Git.


3.2 R and Python


  • R and Rstudio : A democratization of programming

    • easy syntax (grammar)

    • free

    • interactive

    • expanding user-contributed packages

    • several cloud based environments

      • R Cloud

      • R in colaboratory

    • bad memory management

    • can be very slow in certain use cases


  • Python

    • easy syntax (a bit more difficult than R)

    • free

    • native (almost) support in google earth engine

    • popularity (used by major global IT firms)

      • colaboratory
